column2: in Dorsoduro one of the six sestieri of Venice in Veneto

column1: An 18th-century Dominican church a classical style building has a well-lit interior and is exceptional in preserving its original layout and Rococo decoration intact.
The religious order of the Jesuates
column2: formally the Clerici apostolici Sancti Hieronymi was founded in Siena in the 14th century and had a presence in Venice by 1390. Its members were known as I poveri Gesuati (the poor Jesuates) because they frequently called on the name of Jesus.

column1: They acquired some wealth from donations and legacies and from privileges granted by the state
column2: including a monopoly on the distillation of wine. In 1493
column3: they commenced the building of a small church on land fronting the Zattere
column4: which was originally dedicated to St. Jerome.

column1: The order was suppression by Pope Clement IX in 1668
column2: their property was put up for auction and acquired by the Dominicans. The small church was not large enough and by 1720 they had decided to build a new church
column3: larger and of more architectural importance. They first engaged Andrea Musato
column4: but he died in 1721 and they turned to Giorgio Massari
column5: whose model for the new church was accepted in 1724.

column2: while the Dominicans energetically sought to raise sufficient funds
column3: both from charitable contributions and from religious institutions and benefactors. This enabled them not only to build a magnificent church
column4: but to embellish it with the work of the most famous painters and sculptors of the day.

column1: Massari left untouched the existing church of the Visitation
column2: builing the new church around it and further along the Zattere. He was responsible not only for the building itself but also for its interior fittings and decoration and for commissioning the paintings and sculpture. The facade of the church was derived from the central portion of the facade of San Giorgio Maggiore
column3: while the basic idea for the interior came from the Redentore.

column1: Cannaregio is the northernmost of the six historic sestieri (districts) of Venice. It is the second largest sestiere by land area and the largest by population
column3: 169 people as of 2007. Isola di San Michele

column2: which was the main route into the city until the construction of a railway link to the mainland
column3: gave the district its name (Canal Regio is Italian for Royal Canal). Development began in the eleventh century as the area was drained and parallel canals were dredged. Although elegant palazzos were built facing the Grand Canal
column4: the area grew primarily with working class housing and manufacturing. Beginning in 1516
column5: Jews were restricted to living in the Venetian Ghetto.

column1: It was enclosed by guarded gates and no one was allowed to leave from sunset to dawn. However
column2: Jews held successful positions in the city such as merchants
column5: and other trades. Restrictions on daily Jewish life continued for more than 270 years
column6: until Napoleon Bonaparte conquered the Venetian Republic in 1797. He removed the gates and gave all residents the freedom to live where they chose.

column2: civil engineers built a street named Strada Nuova through Cannaregio
column3: and a railway bridge and road bridge were constructed to connect Venice directly to Mestre. Today
column4: the areas of the district along the Grand Canal from the train station to the Rialto Bridge are packed with tourists
column5: but the rest of Cannaregio is residential and relatively peaceful

column1: The Portrait of the Four Tetrarchs probably depicts the four rulers of the Empire instituted by Emperor Diocletian - the first Tetrarchy. column2: but it is suggested that the Eastern rulers form a pair and the Western rulers form the other pair
